00:01:48.750 --> 00:01:52.620
So today we will
delve into Everest.

00:01:52.620 --> 00:01:57.540
So it's kind of Everest season
as it is, and people always

00:01:57.540 --> 00:02:00.670
speak about Everest
this time of year.

00:02:00.670 --> 00:02:03.030
It's the time of year that
people are always on there

00:02:03.030 --> 00:02:04.509
to go climbing.

00:02:04.509 --> 00:02:06.550
As Monica mentioned, I
have a special connection.

00:02:06.550 --> 00:02:09.889
I've been there three times
on three climbing expeditions,

00:02:09.889 --> 00:02:12.550
and then also
subsequent expeditions

00:02:12.550 --> 00:02:16.100
where I've worked
with media, but to set

00:02:16.100 --> 00:02:19.700
the stage from an earth
sciences standpoint--

00:02:19.700 --> 00:02:24.500
and I like Earth sciences--
Mount Everest, or Chomolunga,

00:02:24.500 --> 00:02:27.780
as is known in Tibetan
Sherpa language,

00:02:27.780 --> 00:02:30.140
or Sagarmatha, as it
is known in Nepal,

00:02:30.140 --> 00:02:34.420
is a result of plate tectonics
in the Indian subcontinent

00:02:34.420 --> 00:02:38.050
moving northward at about the
speed our fingernails grow,

00:02:38.050 --> 00:02:40.470
which, if you're
a fan of geology,

00:02:40.470 --> 00:02:42.850
that's supersonic speed.

00:02:42.850 --> 00:02:44.700
It's moving really fast.

00:02:44.700 --> 00:02:48.780
And all that effort of the
Indian plate moving northward

00:02:48.780 --> 00:02:52.560
and subducting into
the Asian land mass

00:02:52.560 --> 00:02:56.520
has created the Himalayas,
and Everest itself

00:02:56.520 --> 00:02:59.600
is a relatively young mountain.

00:02:59.600 --> 00:03:02.530
It's anywhere between
70 and 90 million years

00:03:02.530 --> 00:03:04.580
that that uplift has happened.

00:03:04.580 --> 00:03:10.270
And the summit of Everest
itself is marine limestone.

00:03:10.270 --> 00:03:10.950
There's shale.

00:03:10.950 --> 00:03:12.790
There's Ordovician
limestone that's

00:03:12.790 --> 00:03:14.870
approximately 270
million years old

00:03:14.870 --> 00:03:18.060
that used to be the shallow
inland sea, the Tethys sea,

00:03:18.060 --> 00:03:23.630
off the northern part
of the Asian land--

00:03:23.630 --> 00:03:26.240
the Indian plate that
then is being crunched up.

00:03:26.240 --> 00:03:30.470
So it's not going upward as
much as it's going northward,

00:03:30.470 --> 00:03:32.450
and so there's a deep
root in the mountain,

00:03:32.450 --> 00:03:34.900
and then there's
also, as it moves up,

00:03:34.900 --> 00:03:35.920
it has to go somewhere.

00:03:35.920 --> 00:03:39.910
So imagine if you're at
the table with your kids,

00:03:39.910 --> 00:03:43.150
and you have the tablecloth, and
you push the tablecloth in one

00:03:43.150 --> 00:03:45.700
direction, and it crunches up,
that's how these mountains are

00:03:45.700 --> 00:03:46.670
formed.

00:03:46.670 --> 00:03:49.470
And when you're in the
Himalayas, and you look around,

00:03:49.470 --> 00:03:52.360
and you can tell
the relative age

00:03:52.360 --> 00:03:55.000
and how active a
mountain range is

00:03:55.000 --> 00:03:57.670
by how jagged the skyline is--
so as we look at the pictures

00:03:57.670 --> 00:04:00.822
here in the Himalayas you'll
see that it's really jagged

00:04:00.822 --> 00:04:02.530
and everything, where
you go to someplace

00:04:02.530 --> 00:04:05.070
like the Appalachia, which
is one of the oldest mountain

00:04:05.070 --> 00:04:08.410
ranges on the Earth that's in
the process of eroding away,

00:04:08.410 --> 00:04:13.257
is really an example
of all the mountains

00:04:13.257 --> 00:04:14.840
eventually turn into
the sea, and they

00:04:14.840 --> 00:04:17.519
get recycled, and subducted,
moved around again.

00:04:17.519 --> 00:04:19.510
So that's one of
the neat things I

00:04:19.510 --> 00:04:22.490
like about climbing-- is we
have this very direct connection

00:04:22.490 --> 00:04:23.950
to land mass.

00:04:23.950 --> 00:04:26.470
So if you're out
climbing, you're on a rock

00:04:26.470 --> 00:04:30.000
that's-- if you're in Yosemite,
it's 90 million years old.

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:31.930
You go out in Kenya
where I live it's

00:04:31.930 --> 00:04:33.930
two and a half billion
years old, which predates

00:04:33.930 --> 00:04:35.720
atmospheric oxygen.
So just to be

00:04:35.720 --> 00:04:39.420
able to have that time frame
kind of puts into space

00:04:39.420 --> 00:04:42.190
how insignificant one is.

00:04:42.190 --> 00:04:49.510
This clip here is of the
Khumbu Glacier in Nepal.

00:04:49.510 --> 00:04:51.810
This is a project I did
with the Extreme Ice Survey

00:04:51.810 --> 00:04:53.600
where we set up
time lapse cameras,

00:04:53.600 --> 00:04:55.810
and so this is a
two year time lapse.

00:04:55.810 --> 00:04:59.480
And you can see how the main
Khumbu icefall is moving there.

00:04:59.480 --> 00:05:01.950
So this is the way
that we can then

00:05:01.950 --> 00:05:06.390
use technology to give us data
points and see how things go.

00:05:06.390 --> 00:05:08.200
So it's going to
go in reverse here,

00:05:08.200 --> 00:05:12.100
and you can see the shadow line
there is the azimuth of the sun

00:05:12.100 --> 00:05:15.440
as it moves through, and
you can see how that is.

00:05:15.440 --> 00:05:20.150
I'm fascinated by this way
of looking at glaciers,

00:05:20.150 --> 00:05:25.180
because glaciers are very
much a part of what we do.

00:05:25.180 --> 00:05:28.290
Let's go watch it again
just because it's cool.

00:05:28.290 --> 00:05:31.050
And we've got time, and
we're here at Google,

00:05:31.050 --> 00:05:33.060
and hello to everyone
out there in the cyber

00:05:33.060 --> 00:05:36.560
world that's following along,
but you can look at this.

00:05:36.560 --> 00:05:38.650
You can see how things change.

00:05:38.650 --> 00:05:41.460
This is a two year period
where they're watching it,

00:05:41.460 --> 00:05:45.860
and how the cryosphere,
which is the scientific word

00:05:45.860 --> 00:05:47.860
for the land of
ice that's up there

00:05:47.860 --> 00:05:50.860
and how it's changing--
and one of three ways

00:05:50.860 --> 00:05:54.750
that we can measure glaciers--
or this is the time lapse.

00:05:54.750 --> 00:05:57.156
There's also infrared satellite.

00:05:57.156 --> 00:05:58.780
You can see the
pictures in there.

00:05:58.780 --> 00:06:00.590
There's historical
repeat photography,

00:06:00.590 --> 00:06:02.596
so we can go back
to the earliest

00:06:02.596 --> 00:06:03.970
pictures that were
taken and then

00:06:03.970 --> 00:06:05.870
compare it to where we are now.

00:06:05.870 --> 00:06:10.490
And the high latitude and high
altitude areas of our planet

00:06:10.490 --> 00:06:15.800
are taking a greater hit from
the changing and the warming

00:06:15.800 --> 00:06:17.120
climate than many other places.

00:06:17.120 --> 00:06:21.740
So it's one of these
things that, to me, I'm

00:06:21.740 --> 00:06:22.870
always aware of it.

00:06:22.870 --> 00:06:27.549
And this old joke
in bazooka gum--

00:06:27.549 --> 00:06:29.590
remember, they have the
cartoons wrapped in them,

00:06:29.590 --> 00:06:31.840
those little bricks,
and if they got

00:06:31.840 --> 00:06:34.340
stale, they'd break your
teeth-- but they wrapped around

00:06:34.340 --> 00:06:36.100
one of those was, how
do mountains hear?

00:06:36.100 --> 00:06:37.150
And it said mountaineers.

00:06:37.150 --> 00:06:39.569
And I read that at like age 14.

00:06:39.569 --> 00:06:41.360
I've always kept that
in mind, and now it's

00:06:41.360 --> 00:06:43.314
sort of a mission
in life because I'm

00:06:43.314 --> 00:06:44.730
the eyes and ears
of the mountains

00:06:44.730 --> 00:06:47.960
out there to share
what's going on with it.

00:06:47.960 --> 00:06:52.830
Everest itself was first
measured in 1862-- the Royal

00:06:52.830 --> 00:06:54.120
Trigonometric Survey at India.

00:06:54.120 --> 00:06:56.960
If you like maps--
of course you do.

00:06:56.960 --> 00:06:59.440
You work at Google-- and you
like Earth-- of course you do,

00:06:59.440 --> 00:07:02.880
you work herh-- you get a
chance to see how they measured

00:07:02.880 --> 00:07:06.080
the Indian subcontinent starting
at the southern tip using

00:07:06.080 --> 00:07:10.500
a brass chain taking
into calculations even

00:07:10.500 --> 00:07:13.540
things as humidity and
sag in their chains.

00:07:13.540 --> 00:07:17.110
So they got to within 90
miles of this mountain here,

00:07:17.110 --> 00:07:20.860
and they named it peak 15,
and they measured it out

00:07:20.860 --> 00:07:22.115
to be 29,000 feet.

00:07:22.115 --> 00:07:23.740
That's what their
calculations came to.

00:07:23.740 --> 00:07:26.640
They added two feet to
it because they thought

00:07:26.640 --> 00:07:29.760
that no one would believe
it if it was 29,000 feet,

00:07:29.760 --> 00:07:32.450
and two feet was within
the margin of error,

00:07:32.450 --> 00:07:35.170
but it's interesting to see
that they were less than 1/10

00:07:35.170 --> 00:07:39.930
of 1% of when we look at
the height of either 29,028

00:07:39.930 --> 00:07:45.095
feet or 29,035, or
8848 in meters or 8858

00:07:45.095 --> 00:07:47.190
in meters, which
makes more sense,

00:07:47.190 --> 00:07:50.740
but that they were able to get
that accurate of a measurement

00:07:50.740 --> 00:07:52.040
within that.

00:07:52.040 --> 00:07:56.840
Going on, the surveyor named
it after his predecessor,

00:07:56.840 --> 00:07:59.340
Sir George Everest, and
that was the name Everest,

00:07:59.340 --> 00:08:01.470
and that is where it came from.

00:08:01.470 --> 00:08:06.160
And George Everest himself
was-- he was a humble man.

00:08:06.160 --> 00:08:09.020
He didn't appreciate the
mountain being named after him,

00:08:09.020 --> 00:08:14.240
but it is a very fitting
name, and so it's

00:08:14.240 --> 00:08:16.570
kind of poetic in a
sense that it's Everest

00:08:16.570 --> 00:08:18.330
and it keeps on going.

00:08:18.330 --> 00:08:21.060
So the initial exploration of
Everest once it was measured

00:08:21.060 --> 00:08:24.000
and we knew collectively as
humans the altitude of it,

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:27.650
it began and in 1921.

00:08:27.650 --> 00:08:29.340
That was the very
first expedition,

00:08:29.340 --> 00:08:32.929
and one climber was part
of all three of them.

00:08:32.929 --> 00:08:35.740
Pictured here on--
George Mallory.

00:08:35.740 --> 00:08:39.130
He's the second from the
left over here looking

00:08:39.130 --> 00:08:43.010
quite rakish with his foot up
on his buddy, and to his right--

00:08:43.010 --> 00:08:45.180
left most in the
picture-- is Sandy Irvine,

00:08:45.180 --> 00:08:47.460
and they were-- this is
their third expedition,

00:08:47.460 --> 00:08:50.840
but this was the first attempt
to climb Mount Everest,

00:08:50.840 --> 00:08:54.710
and it was a pretty
special moment.

00:08:54.710 --> 00:08:57.150
England had missed
out on reaching

00:08:57.150 --> 00:08:59.260
the south pole and
the north pole,

00:08:59.260 --> 00:09:01.810
and this was the golden
age of exploration.

00:09:01.810 --> 00:09:03.910
Prior to this,
exploration was very much

00:09:03.910 --> 00:09:07.610
based upon economic means.

00:09:07.610 --> 00:09:12.200
It was there to bring goods
back, to enslave people,

00:09:12.200 --> 00:09:15.950
to have cultural imperialism.

00:09:15.950 --> 00:09:18.910
There's all these different
reasons why we explored,

00:09:18.910 --> 00:09:22.582
but starting in the--
humans, that is--

00:09:22.582 --> 00:09:24.040
and starting in
the 20th century it

00:09:24.040 --> 00:09:28.969
became this goal to explore
for the sake of exploration

00:09:28.969 --> 00:09:30.510
to say you were the
first ones there.

00:09:30.510 --> 00:09:33.170
And of course, the south
pole and Mount Everest

00:09:33.170 --> 00:09:34.260
are both reasons for that.

00:09:34.260 --> 00:09:36.980
I mean, there is no-- Lewis and
Clark went across North America

00:09:36.980 --> 00:09:41.560
to see what was there and
how it can benefit humans,

00:09:41.560 --> 00:09:43.930
but of course there's nothing
grows at the south pole

00:09:43.930 --> 00:09:45.660
nor on the summit of Everest.

00:09:45.660 --> 00:09:50.130
So that eventually became
the first expedition-- 1921,

00:09:50.130 --> 00:09:53.160
'22, and '24, and my
connection to Everest,

00:09:53.160 --> 00:09:56.260
which began in 1999 when
I was part of the Mallory

00:09:56.260 --> 00:09:58.020
and Irvine research
expedition-- we

00:09:58.020 --> 00:10:01.720
set out to solve the
clue as to whether or not

00:10:01.720 --> 00:10:04.220
Sandy Irvine and George
Mallory could have climbed

00:10:04.220 --> 00:10:07.550
Everest 29 years before Sir
Edmund Hillary and Tenzing

00:10:07.550 --> 00:10:09.900
Norgay did in 1953.

00:10:09.900 --> 00:10:14.790
And the 1st of May-- I was at
an elevation of 8,300 meters,

00:10:14.790 --> 00:10:18.480
and I came across the frozen,
well-preserved, and desiccated

00:10:18.480 --> 00:10:19.800
body of George Mallory.

00:10:19.800 --> 00:10:24.570
And while they
did a great effort

00:10:24.570 --> 00:10:26.640
at getting there
on the mountain,

00:10:26.640 --> 00:10:28.400
they didn't make
it to the summit.

00:10:28.400 --> 00:10:31.920
It's my belief just
due to the difficulty

00:10:31.920 --> 00:10:34.977
and what went on with it.

00:10:34.977 --> 00:10:36.810
After that, there were
several expeditions--

00:10:36.810 --> 00:10:42.620
1933, 1936, 1939 through 1945.

00:10:42.620 --> 00:10:43.780
We got in a big argument.

00:10:43.780 --> 00:10:46.560
We fought wars, and
then we came back,

00:10:46.560 --> 00:10:53.070
and it was in 1953 after the
war that on an expedition led

00:10:53.070 --> 00:10:56.880
by Sir George Hunt-- was
able to attain the summit.

00:10:56.880 --> 00:10:59.910
These are some archival
footages courtesy

00:10:59.910 --> 00:11:03.710
of the "National Geographic"
of these early expeditions.

00:11:03.710 --> 00:11:07.180
This is the trip
of 1953 going up

00:11:07.180 --> 00:11:08.820
and climbing on the mountain.

00:11:08.820 --> 00:11:11.260
You can kind of see what it
was like and what they had.

00:11:11.260 --> 00:11:15.220
I mean, here they are
having a cigarette up there.

00:11:15.220 --> 00:11:18.510
We know better than that
now, but they actually

00:11:18.510 --> 00:11:21.960
thought it aided
acclimatization,

00:11:21.960 --> 00:11:23.710
so we know better,
but you can imagine

00:11:23.710 --> 00:11:25.790
climbing across the
glaciers like that,

00:11:25.790 --> 00:11:28.520
looking up onto the
Lhotse faces we see here.

00:11:28.520 --> 00:11:31.110
And at the time, when
I was a young man,

00:11:31.110 --> 00:11:34.150
climbing Everest was sort of the
end all of what climbing was.

00:11:34.150 --> 00:11:36.420
You trained in the mountains,
and you got better,

00:11:36.420 --> 00:11:38.003
and eventually if
you got good enough,

00:11:38.003 --> 00:11:39.820
you'd go to someplace
like Everest.

00:11:39.820 --> 00:11:43.050
And Everest was the
coolest place to go,

00:11:43.050 --> 00:11:46.180
and you can imagine what it was
like climbing in these clothes,

00:11:46.180 --> 00:11:51.090
and as a young man, I used
to dream of this stuff.

00:11:51.090 --> 00:11:56.476
And it was always-- I
guess I was destined

00:11:56.476 --> 00:11:57.850
to be a climber
when I was a kid,

00:11:57.850 --> 00:12:00.590
and we would make pillow
forts and stuff like that.

00:12:00.590 --> 00:12:02.940
And I always pretended
we were in a tent,

00:12:02.940 --> 00:12:04.880
and the wind was blowing.

00:12:04.880 --> 00:12:06.800
It was totally crazy.

00:12:06.800 --> 00:12:09.220
So I just thought I
haven't really grown up.

00:12:09.220 --> 00:12:11.290
I'm still out there
playing a lot,

00:12:11.290 --> 00:12:15.400
but it was the 29th of May,
1953 that Sir Edmund Hillary

00:12:15.400 --> 00:12:19.030
and Tenzing Norgay attained
the summit of Mount Everest.

00:12:19.030 --> 00:12:22.980
And it was a pretty special
moment for the world.

00:12:22.980 --> 00:12:26.420
It was one that was sort of a
relief from the Second World

00:12:26.420 --> 00:12:28.590
War exploration.

00:12:28.590 --> 00:12:30.947
We'd gotten to the South
Pole and the North Pole

00:12:30.947 --> 00:12:32.530
the beginning of the
century, and then

00:12:32.530 --> 00:12:37.130
we had Mount Everest in 1953,
and it was great and fitting

00:12:37.130 --> 00:12:42.860
that it was Ed Hillary from
New Zealand and Tenzing Norgay,

00:12:42.860 --> 00:12:47.070
a Sherpa from Thame
and that part of Nepal

00:12:47.070 --> 00:12:49.090
that they together
were on the summit.

00:12:49.090 --> 00:12:54.070
And this wonderful image of
Tenzing Norgay on the summit

00:12:54.070 --> 00:12:56.200
is pretty iconic.

00:12:56.200 --> 00:13:00.140
It's the one that everyone
associates with it.

00:13:00.140 --> 00:13:02.350
So keep this picture
in mind, and you'll

00:13:02.350 --> 00:13:05.440
see current pictures of
the summit of Everest.

00:13:05.440 --> 00:13:11.480
So you could probably Google
up Everest this season, 2016,

00:13:11.480 --> 00:13:13.230
and you'd see a lot
of people up there,

00:13:13.230 --> 00:13:16.090
and the images, and
the flags, and all

00:13:16.090 --> 00:13:21.440
that other stuff up there,
but the joy of it is here.

00:13:21.440 --> 00:13:24.820
This is why you want
to climb mountains.

00:13:24.820 --> 00:13:30.730
This is Norgay and Hillary after
their ascent in Tengboche--

00:13:30.730 --> 00:13:34.370
just the trust,
the companionship,

00:13:34.370 --> 00:13:36.520
the smile they both have
in there is really, really

00:13:36.520 --> 00:13:37.020
special.

00:13:40.290 --> 00:13:42.990
We have this wonderful
picture of when they came back

00:13:42.990 --> 00:13:45.860
from the coronation,
and the next slide

00:13:45.860 --> 00:13:46.920
does have sound in it.

00:13:46.920 --> 00:13:48.665
So Mike and I did
our AV check here,

00:13:48.665 --> 00:13:51.040
but we're going to wing it
and see if it does have sound.

00:13:51.040 --> 00:13:54.730
If it doesn't have
sound, I'll ad lib.

00:13:54.730 --> 00:13:56.090
So let's see if this works.

00:13:56.090 --> 00:13:56.816
